For your custom enum or struct, you'll need to derive `Debug`, `Display` (or manually implement), and implement `std::error::Error`. The simplest is deriving both traits; then, just override the `source()` method if you want chaining. For example:

```rust
use std::error::Error;
use std::fmt::{self, Display};

#[derive(Debug)]
enum MyError {
    Io(std::io::Error),
    Parse(String),
}

impl Display for MyError {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "My Error")
    }
}

impl Error for MyError {
    fn source(&self) -> Option<&(dyn Error + 'static)> {
        match self {
            MyError::Io(e) => Some(e),
            _ => None,
        }
    }
}
```

You can use a loop with `source()` to walk up the chain:

```rust
fn print_error_chain(err: &dyn Error) {
    let mut e = err;
    while let Some(source) = e.source() {
        println!("Caused by: {}", source);
        e = source;
    }
}
``` This is useful for debugging nested errors.

For that, you can use the `backtrace` crate. It captures a backtrace when an error is created and prints it later. You'd integrate this with your errors like so:

```rust
use std::error::Error;
use std::fmt::{self, Display};
use backtrace::Backtrace;

#[derive(Debug)]
enum MyError {
    Io(std::io::Error),
}

impl Display for MyError {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut fmt::Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "My Error")
    }
}

impl Error for MyError {
    fn source(&self) -> Option<&(dyn Error + 'static)> {
        match self {
            MyError::Io(e) => Some(e),
            _ => None,
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let err = MyError::Io(std::io::Error::new(std::io::ErrorKind::Other, "IO error"));
    println!({}"
}
```
